In Object-Oriented Programming, we can use delegation to achieve this. Delegation is the process of passing a request from one object (the client) onwards and another which will handle it in some way or delegate that task for someone else(in our case List class). 
Here's how you could do something similar:
```java
class SuperList { // superlist as an alias to refer the parent list. It is a common practice when dealing with inheritance hierarchies and delegation scenarios in Java/C# etc...  
    protected ArrayList<String> internalList; 

    public SuperList() {
        this.internalList = new ArrayList<>(); // Initialize your superlist here if needed, e.g., size or other initialization logic..        
    }     
}
class Stack extends SuperList{  
       private int stackSize = 0; 

       public void push(String item) {         
           this.internalList.add(item); // Adding the element to superlist (super list).       
           stackSize++ ;                  // Increment size of Stack   
       }     

       /* This method is delegated from Super List class */ 
       public String pop() {         
         if(stackSize == 0) return null;           
             else{             
                 stackSize--;               
               return this.internalList.get(this.stackSize); // Return the element at specific index in superlist (super list).        } 
       }}  ```   
In your case, you can use `SuperList` instead of directly using List and Stack classes as they are delegating their functionality to a parent class called SuperList which is also maintaining an internal ArrayList. This way we avoid direct inheritance hierarchy in our code making it more flexible for future changes or additions if needed (like adding new methods).

